    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During intense exercise, when the demand for energy outpaces the oxygen supply to the muscles, your body switches to anaerobic respiration. This process, which is faster, produces a byproduct called lactate (often colloquially referred to as lactic acid), which is what causes that burning sensation. The body doesn't actually \"clear\" lactic acid so much as it reprocesses lactate into less acidic compounds, like glucose, through the Cori cycle. It's a complex metabolic balancing act that happens in the liver and muscles.",
      "source": "target",
