    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So, when you're in the middle of a set and that burn really hits, is it just the lactate itself causing the pain, or is there something else happening at the cellular level that makes it feel so disruptive/chaotic in the muscle?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While lactate is certainly involved, the intense burning sensation during high-intensity work is actually a mix of factors, not just the lactate itself. The rapid production of hydrogen ions ($\\text{H}^+$) alongside lactate is what significantly lowers the local $\\text{pH}$ in the muscle tissue. This drop in $\\text{pH}$ interferes with the function of muscle contraction proteins and also stimulates nociceptors, which are the pain receptors in your muscles. It’s this acidity, combined with metabolic stress, that creates that chaotic, burning feeling.",
      "source": "target",
